{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11993"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11993"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.02,0.05,0.74,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59635"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4583"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11993"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45047"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44875"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59635"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old man is brought by ambulance to the Emergency Department following a stab wound to his back. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears anxious. His pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is a 3 cm wound just left of the thoracic spine. He has weakness of his left leg with reduced proprioception, and decreased pain and temperature sensation in his right leg below the level of injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior cord syndrome","Cauda equina syndrome","Central cord syndrome","Brown-Sequard syndrome","Spinal shock"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of \u003Cstrong\u003EBrown-Sequard syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E: ipsilateral motor weakness, ipsilateral proprioception loss, and contralateral pain and temperature sensation loss below the level of injury. This syndrome typically results from hemisection of the spinal cord, most commonly due to penetrating trauma as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cord syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E affects the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, resulting in bilateral motor weakness and loss of pain/temperature sensation below the level of injury, while preserving proprioception and vibration sense due to sparing of the dorsal columns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauda equina syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E presents with bilateral symptoms including saddle anaesthesia, bowel/bladder dysfunction, and bilateral leg weakness. It typically results from compression of nerve roots below the level of the conus medullaris.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral cord syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically causes greater weakness in the upper limbs than lower limbs, often following hyperextension injuries in elderly patients with cervical spondylosis. It may also cause varying degrees of sensory loss and bladder dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinal shock\u003C/strong\u003E presents with complete, bilateral loss of all neurological function (motor, sensory, and autonomic) below the level of injury. It is a temporary physiological response to acute spinal cord injury rather than a specific anatomical pattern of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anatomical basis for Brown-Sequard syndrome relates to the organisation of spinal cord tracts. The corticospinal tracts and dorsal columns ascend ipsilaterally, explaining the same-side weakness and proprioception loss. The spinothalamic tracts decussate within a few segments of entering the cord, explaining the contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brown-Sequard syndrome presents with ipsilateral motor weakness and proprioception loss, with contralateral pain and temperature sensation loss below the level of injury","Penetrating trauma is the most common cause of Brown-Sequard syndrome","The clinical pattern results from hemisection of the spinal cord affecting different ascending and descending tracts"],"references":["Shams S, Arain A. Brown Sequard Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Jul 17. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538135/","McKinley W, Santos K, Meade M, Brooke K. Incidence and outcomes of spinal cord injury clinical syndromes. J Spinal Cord Med. 2007;30(3):215-24. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2031952/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45047"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11993"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45047"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T15:02:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T14:07:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4583"}},"content":{"data":{"t